==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|xno}} {{term|cotidian}}, {{term|cotidien}}, {{etyl|frm}} {{term|cotidian}}, {{term|cotidien}}, and their source, {{etyl|la}} {{term|cottidianus|cottīdiānus}}, {{term|quotidianus|quōtīdiānus|happening every day|lang=la}}, from {{term|cottidie|cottīdiē}}, {{term|quotidie|quōtīdiē|every day, daily|lang=la}}, from an unattested adjective derived from {{term|quot||how many|lang=la}} + locative form of {{term|dies|diēs|day|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/kwəˈtɪdɪən/}}
* {{audio|en-us-quotidian.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# {{medicine}} Recurring every twenty-four hours or (more generally) [[daily]] (of symptoms etc.). {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
# Happening every day; [[daily]]. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
# Having the characteristics of something which can be seen, experienced etc. every day or very commonly; [[common]], [[ordinary]], [[trivial]], [[mundane]]. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}

